In a LaTeX document, you can generate a table of contents automatically using the `tableofcontents` environment. Here's an example of how to do this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

% Step 1: Define the title of the document
\title{My Document Title}

% Step 2: Generate the table of contents
\maketitle

% Step 3: Create a new section for each chapter or major section in your document
\section{Section 1}
\section{Section 2}
\section{Section 3}

% Step 4: Generate the table of contents
\tableofcontents

\chapter{Chapter 1}
\chapter{Chapter 2}
\chapter{Chapter 3}

\section{Section 4}
\section{Section 5}
\section{Section 6}

\printindex

\end{document}
```

In this example, the table of contents is generated automatically by the `tableofcontents` environment, which is typically called after the document title and before the main content. The sections and chapters in your document will be listed in the table of contents.

The `\maketitle` command is used to generate the document title, and the `\printindex` command is used to generate the index (if it exists) in the document. 

Please note that the actual content of the sections and chapters (like the text in the `.md` files) is not provided in this example, but you would replace the placeholders `\section{Section 1}`, `\section{Section 2}`, etc. with the actual titles of your sections and chapters. 

Also, the `article` class is used here, but you can choose a different class depending on your document's requirements. For instance, if you're writing a book, you might choose the `book` class.
